{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012eQDjze7VeZ7ggLDvRU5Fi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the info I need:\n\n1. The main Elasticsearch cluster is in the `elasticsearch` namespace, running version 8.11.1 with:\n   - HTTPS enabled with TLS\n   - Basic auth: `elastic:elasticpass`\n   - CA cert available in `es-http-tls` secret\n   - Logs at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs`\n   \n2. The monitoring cluster is in the `monitoring` namespace, running version 7.17.9 with:\n   - Plain HTTP on port 9200\n   - Service: `monitoring-es-http.monitoring.svc.cluster.local:9200`\n   - No authentication\n\nMy approach will be to create ConfigMaps in the `elasticsearch` namespace for Metricbeat and Filebeat configurations, then patch the StatefulSet to add these as sidecars. I need to be mindful of the version mismatch—Metricbeat 8.11.1 will monitor the main cluster while sending metrics to the older 7.17.9 monitoring cluster, which should work fine for stack monitoring purposes.\n\nFor Metricbeat, I'm configuring it to run as a sidecar using version 8.11.1, connecting to the local Elasticsearch node via HTTPS with the CA certificate and elastic credentials, then outputting to the monitoring cluster's HTTP endpoint using the elasticsearch module with stack_monitoring collection. Filebeat will also run as a sidecar at the same version, collecting JSON logs from Elasticsearch and shipping them to the monitoring cluster.\n\nNow I need to check what TLS certificates and credentials are available in the es-http-tls secret.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1268,"cache_read_input_tokens":33155,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1268},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"p