{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HYN3PYfynqxdTARidW5pbM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The logs directory is on the overlay filesystem (part of the container's main filesystem), not a separate volume. I'll need to add an emptyDir volume and mount it at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs` so both the ES container and the Filebeat sidecar can access the logs.\n\nNow let me plan the complete solution:\n\n1. Create `metricbeat-config` ConfigMap in `elasticsearch` namespace with Metricbeat config\n2. Create `filebeat-config` ConfigMap in `elasticsearch` namespace with Filebeat config\n3. Patch the StatefulSet to:\n   - Add `ES_LOG_STYLE=file` to the `elasticsearch` container's env\n   - Add an `es-logs` emptyDir volume and mount it at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs` in the ES container\n   - Add Metricbeat and Filebeat sidecars\n\nFor Metricbeat, I need to configure it to connect to the local ES instance at `https://localhost:9200` using the provided credentials, enable the elasticsearch module, and send metrics to the monitoring cluster. For Filebeat, I'll configure it to read the JSON-formatted server logs from the shared volume, use the elasticsearch module, and forward them to monitoring as well. Configuring Filebeat modules... The monitoring bulk API is the right approach here for shipping data in the proper format. I should stick with using Metricbeat and Filebeat 8.11.1 to match the main cluster version, which will handle the monitoring data correctly when configured to output to the 7.17.9 monitoring cluster.\n\nWriting Metricbeat config... Confirming the log file path by checking how Elasticsearch generates it through log4j2 configuration — the cluster name `es-cluster` combined with the logs base path gives me `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs/es-cluster_server.json`, which matches what I have in the Filebeat config. The Filebeat elasticsearch module with xpack monitoring enabled is the right approach here.\n\nConfiguring the Filebeat elasticsearch module... Writing the patch... Configuring filebeat container... I'm second-guessing whether Filebeat's elasticsearch module actually supports `xpack.enabled` at the module level like Metricbeat does, so I need to verify the correct configuration approach for shipping monitoring data through Filebeat versus just regular logs. Writing configuration examples... The server JSON log would be at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs/es-cluster_server.json`, which is where I'll point Filebeat to read from. For Filebeat configuration, I'm disabling ILM since the monitoring cluster is on 7.17.9, though templates still need to be enabled for proper indexing. With Metricbeat's `xpack.enabled: true`, the monitoring bulk API handles the data routing, so I don't need explicit index templates from Metricbeat itself. Since they're the same version, Metricbeat should work perfectly against the ES cluster. I'm realizing that `output.elasticsearch` pointing to the monitoring cluster is the right approach when using `xpack.enabled: true`, and I don't need `setup.monitoring` since I just want Metricbeat to monitor the main cluster and ship the data to the monitoring cluster. Now I'll finalize the configuration and create the configmaps using kubectl.\n\nFor the StatefulSet patch, I'm adding the necessary environment variables, volumes, and sidecar containers through a strategic merge patch. The patch will include the `ES_LOG_STYLE=file` variable, the logs volume, configmap volumes for both beat configs, and the Metricbeat and Filebeat sidecars with their volume mounts. A rolling update will be triggered since I'm modifying the pod spec, and with three pods and a green cluster, this should be safe to proceed with.\n\nWriting the patch YAML... Writing Kubernetes manifest... Adding the new environment variable and volume mount to the container spec, then reconsidering the Filebeat configuration to use a raw log input instead of the Elasticsearch module for more flexibility with the JSON log format. get shipped to the monitoring cluster and create the appropriate monitoring indices. So I need to ensure both sidecars are configured to output to the monitoring cluster's Elasticsearch instance, and that they're using the right index patterns or modules that generate monitoring-type indices. I should disable ILM to keep things simple and avoid permission issues. For both Metricbeat and Filebeat, I'm configuring the container args to point to the custom config files and disable strict permissions since the ConfigMap files won't have the expected permissions.\n\nNow I need to handle the TLS connection to Elasticsearch—the pods use self-signed certificates, so I'll mount the CA cert from the `es-http-tls` secret into the Metricbeat container rather than skipping verification entirely. Let me write out the complete solution with all these pieces in place. Writing the kubectl commands... I'm realizing I'm overcomplicating this with manual configuration. The Filebeat Elasticsearch module is purpose-built for stack monitoring and handles the index naming and template setup automatically, so I should leverage that instead of trying to configure everything manually.\n\nHowever, there's a potential version mismatch between Filebeat 8.11.1 and Elasticsearch 7.17.9 that could cause template compatibility issues. Let me switch to a simpler filestream input approach that parses the NDJSON logs directly, adds the necessary cluster metadata fields, and sends them to the monitoring cluster.\n\nWriting Filebeat config...\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. The core requirement is just to get monitoring indices created and both sidecars running. Let me use Metricbeat with xpack enabled for the main metrics collection—that's the standard approach and will generate the proper `.monitoring-es-7-mb-*` indices—and pair it with a basic Filebeat filestream input to ship logs to the monitoring cluster. I don't need to