{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Fpm3G9M7vjZvnAw5zfajq3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, the loop condition is wrong. Let me fix it. The condition should loop WHILE there are pods that don't have \"3/3\". Let me check the logic again.\n\nActually, looking at my command:\n```bash\nuntil kubectl get pods -n elasticsearch | grep -E \"^es-[0-9]\" | awk '{print $2}' | grep -v \"3/3\" | grep -qv \"^$\"\n```\n\nThis says:\n- `grep -v \"3/3\"` - get lines that don't have 3/3\n- `grep -qv \"^$\"` - check if there are any non-empty lines, returning success when they exist\n\nSo the until loop continues while the command fails (returns non-zero), meaning it keeps looping as long as there are pods without \"3/3\" ready.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the logic here - the command should succeed when all pods ARE at 3/3, which means the grep for non-3/3 pods should find nothing.  Using `grep -qv \"3/3\"` in a while loop works because it succeeds when there's at least one pod not ready, so the loop continues while pods are still starting up. So the `until` condition is backwards—it keeps looping while there ARE pods not at 3/3, when I need it to loop until all pods reach 3/3. Looking at the actual output, es-0 is only 1/1 and es-1 is 2/3, so the rollout isn't actually complete despite the script saying it is. I need to reconsider the logic here. The `grep -qv \"3/3\"` command exits with 0 when there are pods not at 3/3, and exits with 1 when all pods are at 3/3. So I want to loop while that condition is true (while there are pods not ready), which means I should use `while` instead of `until`, or flip the logic entirely. So `until` checks the condition first and exits if it's true, which means the loop stopped immediately since there were already pods not at 3/3. I need to flip this to a `while` loop that continues as long as pods aren't ready, checking the pod status repeatedly until they all reach 3/3.\n\nSince I already have a rollout status command running in the background, I should just check that output to see when it completes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":499,"cache_read_input_tokens":52984,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":499},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"262bb4ad-adb6-41a1-8918-e63b58536b56","uuid":"0a173f6b-b87b-4716-9768-8f1a7d4ec4f7","request_id":"req_011CcQBaShDCEkYMrEL1h7Az"}
